site_name: Phase 4 Of The Acton Gardens Masterplan;
description: Reserved matters application for Phase 4 of the Acton Gardens masterplan detailing Landscaping, Appearance, Scale, Access and Layout in relation to the construction of a part seven to nine storey high apartment building containing 107 units (33 no. 1-bedroom, 46 no. 2-bedroom, 25 no. 3-bedroom, and 3 no. 4-bedroom flats); associated private and semi-private amenity space, refuse / recycling and bicycle stores; a single-storey substation; 18 off-street car parking spaces and 19 on-street car parking spaces; provision of a public open space of approximately 4,900 sq.m; the closure of Hanbury Road and reconfiguration of the public highway to the east of its current position and the construction of a new north-south street between Bollo Bridge Road and Osborne Road; application made part pursuant to conditions 2 (Reserved Matters), 4 (Reserved Matters Details), 5 (Details of Public Realm Landscaping), 6 (Energy Strategy), 11 (Noise Mitigation Measures), 16 (Flood Risk Assessment), 18 (Tree Protection), 19 (Refuse and Recycling Enclosures), 20 (Archaeological Investigation), 22 (Rainwater and / or Greywater Recycling Systems), 25 (Boundary Treatments), 26 (Details of Secured by Design) and 35 (Timeframe for the Delivery of West Park) of outline planning permission LBE ref: P/2012/0708, dated 13/08/2013 (amended by minor material amendment application PP/2014/2142, dated 21/07/2014) for the multi-Phased regeneration of the South Acton Estate.
decision_conditions: The development hereby approved shall be carried out in accordance with the following approved plans and documents:   Drawings: (1409_PL_) 000 A, 001 A, 002 D, 101 F, 102 C, 103 C, 104 C, 105 C, 106 C, 107 C, 108 C, 109 C, 110, 151 C, 152 C, 153 C, 154 C, 155 C, 156 C, 157 C, 158 C, 159 C, 451 C, 452 C, 453 C, 454 D, 455 D, 456 D, 457 D, 458 D, 459 D, 460 C, 461 C, 462 C, 463 D, 464 C, 465 D, 466 C, 467 C, 468 D, 469 D, 470 D, 471 D, 472 D, 473 C, 475 B, 176 B, 200 B, 201 B, 210 B, 211 B, 250 A, 700; LD-GA-100 F, LD-GA-105 E, LD-RD-001 C, SEC-400 C;   Technical reports: Planning Supporting Statement (including Affordable Housing Statement, Estate Management Strategy, and Statement of Community Involvement), prepared by Terence O'Rourke; Design and Access Statement prepared by PCKO; Landscape Design Statement with Addendum Rev A, dated 22/12/2014, prepared by LUC; Daylight and Sunlight Performance Analysis (October 2014), prepared by GVA; Energy Strategy, prepared by Mendick Waring; Code for Sustainable Homes Pre-Assessment, prepared by Mendick Waring; Environmental Noise Assessment (Report No: SRB/6812), prepared by AIRO; Foul and Surface Water Drainage Scheme, Foul and Surface Water Drainage Statement (B) (dated 13.10.2014), Estimate of Existing Run-Off (dated 13.08.2014) and supporting drawings (Existing Area Plan, Proposed Area Plan, A2601 SK1500), prepared by Colin Toms and Partners; Arboricultural Report and Tree Condition Survey ref: 1114-1689 Rev 2 (dated December 2014) and TPP-01 Rev 1 (Tree Protection Plan), prepared by Ruskins Group Consultancy; Archaeology - Written Scheme of Investigation, prepared by Pre-Construct Archaeology Ltd; Water Statement, prepared by Mendick Waring; Transport Statement, prepared by i-Transport; Confidential Financial Viability Appraisal, prepared by Countryside Properties; Product Guide and Case Studies - Josta 2-tier cycle storage.  Reason: For the avoidance of doubt and in the interests of proper planning. | There shall be a minimum six-month establishment period for the approved West Park landscaping scheme prior to the first occupation of the approved apartment building.  Reason: The provision of West Park is an integral and significant part of the approved development required in order to mitigate the loss of the existing South Park designated Public Open Space, and to ensure that open space is provided for the benefit of the local community, and in order that the development is provided in accordance with the policy requirements set out at paragraph 74 of the NPPF and policies 7.2, 7.3, 7.5 and 7.18 of the London Plan 2011; policies 1.1(e), 1.1(i), 1.2(d) and 2.1(c) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012, and policy 7D of Ealing's adopted Development Management DPD 2013. | Prior to the commencement of any part of the development affecting the location or use of the existing bus stop within the application site, details for the temporary (if applicable) and permanent relocation of the bus stop, and a works phasing plan, shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority, in consultation with Transport for London. The details shall include an accompanying safety audit and recommendations for improvements to the permanent bus stop.  The relocated temporary (if applicable) and permanent bus stop shall be provided in accordance with the agreed work phasing plan and the cost of the provision shall be borne by the developer.  Reason: To ensure that the bus stop affected by the proposed development is provided to an acceptable standard and in a timely fashion, and that temporary provision is made during the construction of the development,  in accordance with policies 6.2, 6.10, 7.2 and 7.5 of the London Plan 2011; policies 1.1(e) and 1.1(g) and 6.1 of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012.
